{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:01:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.18,0.55,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111976"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94040"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10724"},{"type":"tags","id":"10728"},{"type":"tags","id":"11614"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45846"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111976"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concern about an inherited condition in her family. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a teacher, does not smoke, and drinks alcohol socially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter taking a family history, you drew the pedigree as shown below.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most commonly follows the inheritance pattern described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duchenne muscular dystrophy","Haemophilia A","Huntington disease","Cystic fibrosis","Sickle cell disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding inheritance patterns allows clinicians in primary care to triage who may benefit from genetic counselling and testing. Vertical transmission through multiple generations, equal sex distribution, and the possibility of male-to-male transmission are hallmarks of autosomal dominant inheritance. In contrast, X-linked recessive inheritance typically affects males with no male-to-male transmission, and autosomal recessive conditions often show horizontal clustering among siblings with unaffected parents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant neurodegenerative disorder caused by a CAG repeat expansion in the HTT gene. The described pattern of affected individuals in every generation, both sexes involved, and male-to-male transmission matches autosomal dominant inheritance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia A\u003C/strong\u003E is X-linked recessive. Affected males inherit the variant from carrier mothers, and affected fathers do not pass the condition to their sons, so male-to-male transmission does not occur, which conflicts with the described pedigree.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is autosomal recessive. Affected individuals usually have unaffected carrier parents, and the pattern often appears horizontal among siblings rather than vertical through generations, making it less consistent with the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuchenne muscular dystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is X-linked recessive with predominantly affected boys and no male-to-male transmission, which is inconsistent with the reported male-to-male transmission and vertical pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell disease\u003C/strong\u003E is autosomal recessive. As with other autosomal recessive conditions, affected individuals often arise when both parents are carriers, producing a pattern that is not typically vertical through each generation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autosomal dominant conditions show vertical transmission across generations with approximately half of offspring affected irrespective of sex.","Male-to-male transmission supports autosomal dominant inheritance and argues against X-linked inheritance."],"references":["Hydra2114, CC BY-SA 4.0 \u003Chttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0\u003E, via Wikimedia Commons","Frost DA. GeNotes. [cited 2025 Aug 20]. Autosomal dominant inheritance \u2014 Knowledge Hub. Available from: https://www.genomicseducation.hee.nhs.uk/genotes/knowledge-hub/autosomal-dominant-inheritance/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94040"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22062"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22062"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/00UEFLRZ8oSFdY78qdPIs3ARMyAVsg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/00UEFLRZ8oSFdY78qdPIs3ARMyAVsg.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94040"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T14:58:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T14:58:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8249"}},"conte